{
  "$comment": "GOLDEN VECTORS for the op-batch binary wire protocol defined in op-batch-wire.json. Each entry is a batch (the guest-side SerializedOperationBatch JSON) paired with its EXACT expected on-the-wire encoding as a lowercase hex string. These are the fixed cross-language ORACLE: an encoder must produce 'hex' byte-for-byte, and a decoder must reconstruct 'batch' from 'hex' — so encoder and decoder cannot silently drift together (a bug that agrees on both sides still fails the golden). Vectors assume a FRESH encoder per batch (intern table starts empty, indices from 0), header.flags = NONE (no timestamps), and the number rule (integers in i32 range -> INT32, else FLOAT64). All scalars little-endian. 'byteLength' is len(hex)/2. The 'breakdown' annotates each byte group for human review; it is documentation, not part of the wire.",
  "version": 1,
  "vectors": [
    {
      "name": "empty-batch",
      "description": "Zero operations: header + an empty intern table. The irreducible floor of the format = 18 bytes.",
      "batch": { "version": 1, "batchId": 0, "operations": [] },
      "hex": "52494c4c0100000000000000000000000000",
      "byteLength": 18,
      "breakdown": [
        { "bytes": "52494c4c", "field": "magic 'RILL' (0x4c4c4952 LE)" },
        { "bytes": "0100", "field": "version = 1" },
        { "bytes": "00000000", "field": "batchId = 0" },
        { "bytes": "0000", "field": "opCount = 0" },
        { "bytes": "00", "field": "flags = NONE" },
        { "bytes": "000000", "field": "reserved[3]" },
        { "bytes": "0000", "field": "intern count = 0" }
      ]
    },
    {
